SIMPLE: pervious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pervious
<hw>Per"vi*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pervis</ets>; <ets>per</ets> + <ets>via</ets> a way. See
<er>Per-</er>, and <er>Voyage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Admitting
passage; capable of being penetrated by another body or substance;
permeable; <as>as, a <ex>pervious</ex> soil</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Doors] . . . <qex>pervious</qex> to winds, and open every
way.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of being penetrated, or seen through, by
physical or mental vision.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God, whose secrets are <qex>pervious</qex> to no eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Capable of penetrating or pervading.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Open; -- used synonymously with
<altname>perforate</altname>, as applied to the nostrils or
birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perviousness</ent>⟦br⟧
